title: For Sale:  Hamilton Model 7 Boys Rifle
postcontent: Hamilton Model Number 7 Single Shot Boy's RifleMfd Dates 1899 - 1901Model 7 was the first Hamilton Rifle made. The skeleton frame was made entirely of castings, stampings with coil springs and completely nickel-plated. To load the rifle the barrel pivots to the left at the frame junction, exposing the chamber. A small arm manually ejects the spent case. Clarence Hamiltom and his partners owned Plymouth Windmill Company. Clarence and another fellow made metal air rifles that were sold or given away with windmills. The air rifle buisness soon bacame better than the windmill sales. Plymouth air rifles models 1-6 were made at this plant. Clarence wanted to make a low cost boys rifle and the Hamilton Model 7 was born. He sold off the air rifle and windmill companies and focused on building rifles with his sons. In 1942 the company stopped building rifle to support the war effort. The company never rebounded after the war partially due to failing health of Clarence. Plymouth Air Rifles changed their name to Daisy and you know the rest of that story. The Hamilton No 7 still holds the record for the longest firing pin on a shoulder fired rifle at 9" long.44,700 No. 7's were made from 1899-1901, of which Mr. Ringbauer, Hamilton Rifle Historian, Author and Collector, estimates 99.9 percent have gone to "Rifle Heaven". Reguardless, very few of the rifle exsist. This rifle is fully functional. It does cock and fire. The bore is in great shape but it s missingsome of the plating.The email function has not been working since ArmList  upgraded their site. title: For Sale:  RARE 12 ga FRENCH TABATIERE  "ZULU" SHOTGUN
postcontent: This very rare firearm started life in 1857 as a muzzle loader, the largest caliber ever made, around 54 caliber.  During the Franco/Prussian War it was converted to a breech loading rifle.  Later the French armed the Zulus with these guns in their struggle with England to colonize Africa.  Some made their way to America where they were used in the Civil War, firing Minie ball ammo.  Finally, it was converted to a 12 gauge shotgun, many times serving as the primary firearm among early Western settlers and used by them for both protection and hunting.  This particular gun is in original condition as far as I can tell.  Everything is true to the final shotgun modification in the 19th century, including screws and hardware.  The breech is brass, the hammer and firing pin operate perfectly and the finish on the stock appears original.  Chambers a modern 12 gauge shell.  This beauty is really one of a kind to add to your collection.  I'll gladly show it anywhere in the Johnson City area

title: For Sale:  Johnson Model of 1941
postcontent: The Johnson Model of 1941 is a semiautomatic 30-06 battle rifle that competed against the M-1 for use as the US Military battle rifle. Johnson lore says it should have won, but the testing required the use of US Military Ammo. The M-1 used 7.62 x51 current production ammo. the Johnson was relegated to 30-06 WW1 ammunition and had several failures to fire feed or eject. Who knows? Anyway, this is one of about 78000 made. Never issued in the US, was used by several other nations. Original, with original wood, sights, metal butt plate. No bayonet. These list across the US anywhere from $6000 up depending on condition and accessories. Helping a military widow with this sale. As a WW2 era semi auto, this is C&R type weapon. Asking $5500. Use 30mm rings or quick release mount to match your firearms platform.
